The composites present relatively low concentration contrast to the pure n-Bi2Te3,(Fig. 3i) which attributing to the high Seebeck coefficient. For the n-type Bi2Te3 (Bi2Te2.68Se0.32) samples with 423 K-, 593 K- annealing, the values are relatively low (1.45 × 1018–1 × 1019 cm−3) compared to typical bulk Bi2Te3-based materials, which is answerable for the comparatively poor electrical conducting performance of 623 K-, 673 K- annealed samples, as well as other related bulk materials (Supplementary Fig. 9d). This is because the lower the annealing temperature, the higher the Se content in the semiconductors which will lead to the reduced carrier density. When doping with the Se in the Bi2Te3 system, Se will occupies the Te vacancies and make up two free electrons forming the SeTe anti-defects, that is, Se+VTe+2e−=SeTe\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
